SOAKING & SOURING LENTILS/ GRAINS/ BEANS

Truth- Indians have known about soaking, sprouting & fermenting lentils for centuries

But how many of us actually bother with this age old tradition (except when we make dosa or idli batter)

Zanu went off her khichadi and dal at around age 2 and has just started eating varan bhat again (yay), just when I read in @rujuta.diwekar ‘s book Notes On Healthy Kids, that kids go off lentils around age 2 because the phytic acid in there actually prevents mineral absorption and they naturally start eating it again.

But if you help the digestability (fake word 😂), it will help your kid (and you) absorb all that good nutrition better, making it -watch out for trending nutritionist word here- BIO-AVAILABLE!

It’s a very simple process.
1. PLAN- what you are eating for the next day 😂 esp if it’s dal, grains or beans
2. RINSE- your lentils/ beans 3-4 times till water runs clear
3. COVER- with warm water
4. ADD ACID- yogurt, kefir, apple cider vinegar or lemon juice
5. QUANTITY- 1 tbsp acid - 1 cup water 
6. SOAK- overnight or minimum 8 hours
7. RINSE- well and cook

Also lessons I learnt while cooking dal without a pressure cooker from you guys- 
1. DON’T ADD SALT
2. ADD WHEY FROM PANEER IF YOU HAVE
3. CAN COOK DAL IN THE OVEN! 
4. DEFINITELY SOAK (which I did!)
5. ADD A LITTLE FAT

Or just carry a bloody pressure cooker wherever you go 😂

Do you soak, sprout, sour or ferment? Tell me!!

ALL YOU NEED TO KNOW ABOUT GLUTEN & GLUTEN FREE SWAPS.

Even though we eat a lot of gluten, adding a variety of millets & gluten free foods in your family’s diet is wise. @amala.earth has some amazing GLUTEN FREE OPTIONS that I want to tell you about but FIRST-
why is gluten suddenly making us sick!??

We are eating BAD WHEAT.
It’s over-processed, badly grown and badly prepared.

Case in point being that when most gluten intolerant people eat a properly slow-fermented sourdough, they don’t have most of the reactions they do when eating, say, packet white bread.

Watch the video to see how our ancestors did it differently and never had to be one of those ‘dietary restrictions’ people at a party!

Now for the SWAPS!

Amaranth Flour- I love the seedy, nutty taste of this flour in chapatis, baking, cookies and it even makes an amazing polenta-style khichadi. Also it takes very little water and grows super easily in India which is something to consider

Almond Flour- how to make gluten free cakes and cookies and muffins that don’t taste like cardboard? Almond flour is my go-to for any kind of baking! Esp our flourless chocolate cake and almond flour muffins!

Hemp Protein Powder- Hemp is our country’s true heritage!! This is the land of Sativa Indica! It is also one of the least processed protein powders which is something to consider!

Gluten free biscuits- now this is where I usually draw the line too! My parents eat the WORST biscuits thinking they are ‘healthy’! Zanu absolutely loves the Oats Cranberry & Chia Turmeric Cookies available on @amalaearth and has been eating them since she was about 1.5 years old.

So there it is- must we demonise something to eat healthier? Nope. Just try and get good quality, stone milled, unrefined wheat and soak, sprout & ferment it properly.
And also eat all the other gluten-free good stuff.
Don’t become a #glutentroll 😂

Chakra Affirmations

In my curious early twenties, my mom and me went for a Chakra workshop
One amazing thing about the workshop was that we were each given a crystal and taught how to move it with our minds. I swear- think STOP, it would stop moving. Think CLOCKWISE, it would go clockwise. I kid you not.
Even more amazing, the crystal could read whether your chakra was open or closed. Clockwise meant open, anti-clockwise meant shut, stuck diagonal movement meant half-open/ half-shut.
And THE MOST AMAZING THING- if you said an affirmation to release the blocks and then a positive one with respect to that particular chakra, the next reading would be open. You could actually physically open your chakras with affirmations. 
Cool right!
So here are some chakra affirmations I do when I feel I need to ground, release and affirm. 
p.s- Ignore the corny ecstatic expression on my face, I’ve never filmed myself doing this before, I look really cheesy 😂

Root chakra/ Muladhara- Lam- Red- I release all fear/ I am protected, guided and beloved of the universe
Sacral chakra/ Svadhistana- Vam- Orange- I release all guilt/ I am open to my sensuality & pleasure
Solar Plexus Chakra/ Manipura- Ram- Yellow- I release all anger & tension/ I flow with the power that created me
Heart Chakra/ Anahata- Yam- Green- I release all hurt & sadness/ I give & take unconditional love
Throat Chakra/ Vishuddha- Ham- Sky Blue- I release all blocks to my communication/ I am in open two way communion with the universe
Third Eye/ Ajna- Aum/ Indigo- I clear my doors if perception/ I am connected to my higher self
Crown Chakra/ Sahasrara/ Violet/ No sound- I am one with the cosmos.

As I come out of an intense week of Covid, I see how a constructive spirituality and daily rituals can really help in low times. 
What are your morning rituals?

Hellllooooo Covid!
From an unexpected little unicorn, madam Zanu.
Well if there was one to get, this was it!
I was quite shocked I didn’t already have it, considering the number of people I know this time who got it.
What I like about what @drniharparekh is saying here is-
- if one person/ child has it, most likely everyone is getting it so you don’t need to quarantine on your own
- don’t stop living your life because of the fear! Zanu had high fever for the first day (and of course that’s hard for any parent) but it was already down by the second day (yesterday) and today she is dressed in her unicorn outfit and is trying to ‘take care of me’

What is important is getting tested, to give yourself and people around you a proper heads up, then leave them to follow whichever treatment or method they want to follow.

Our Goa homeopath told us not to take paracetamol (but we did for both Z & I). He also told us loads of fluids, electral with 3 lemons squeezed into it + ginger juice and lots and lots of fresh orange juice with the pulp. 
@realhomoeopathy has a whole Covid protocol and I intend on starting that today.
I was feeling horrible in the morning (headache was too bad to even watch @netflix_in what the hell) and I have fever but yay antibody party starts today!! 

Yes to herd immunity, yes to endemic, yes to kids being in school (even though Zanu got it from there), yes to taking proper precautions, being safe but also letting go OF THE FEAR. 

On that note though, I do feel if schools are going to reopen, there needs to be a proper follow through of sick kids (and their sick parents).

I finally feel like I’ve arrived at the #covidparty !

My fellow covidians 😂

Send us healing hugs! And Enterntainment tips. And what to eat and drink. 

Chris is doing a fantastic job of looking after Z and me (and seems to be a bit miffed that he doesn’t have it yet and has to wait on us)

TRAVEL FOOD! What to carry!
This might seem a little off considering everyone is probably about to cancel all travel plans indefinitely butttttt if you are planning to travel with a 2-4 year old… EVER.. this might be a useful survival kit.
It’s now much much smaller than what we used to lug around when she was a baby. And honestly Z was amazing this trip, tried everything and stayed up for dinner every night no matter where we were (some nights were tougher than others)
What I consider essentials these days are things that I know she wakes up to, healthy snacks for the road and some survival stock for the parents!

DUDU- If your kid is like Zanu and wakes up to milk then having a few emergency packets is always advisable. Along with honey that we drink with it. And her favorite purple glass. And her favorite steel straw.
HEALTHY(ISH) SNACKS- we carried khakra, tacos, @evolve ragi sticks, @ambrosiaorganicfarm rice cakes, @natchsnacks rice crackers, @tatasoulfull choco ragi pops, @nourish.organics cookies, @monsoonharvest granola bars, goji berries, dates, some homemade shortbread cookies (hence the ish in the healthy-ish), more dry fruits, apples, @offeringsfarms passion fruit, blueberries, @paperboatdrinks juices

CUTLERY/ CROCKERY- we always carry reusable cutlery & stainless steel straws from @be.ecological and a cup, bowl & plate from @altretail @boboandboo . A friend’s genius idea is to also carry an empty dabba to pack all the leftovers your kid doesn’t eat at the restaurant. A small knife (swiss army knife will do) is always a good idea too!

For the parents! 
COFFEE/TEA- good coffee (or decaf for me) as soon as you wake up is a must or your favorite tea bags + electric kettle + French press + sugar

ALCOHOL- we carried whiskey, sake & red wine for those sunset aperitifs. Chris of course drank cold beer from wherever we were.

Zanu has finally moved on from the super-selective food hump and tried everything and was pretty amazing!

ठेच्याचा ठ is BACK! If you commented on yesterday’s post before it was taken down pls comment again, they were super fun!
If you love #VBTL (varan bhat tup limboo) then you MUST eat it with THECHA.
These are the pickles we make at home- thecha, mirchi cha loncha (made with mustard), goda loncha (with kairi, short shelf life), kairicha loncha (long lasting spicy version), sweet limbacha loncha (my fave), shengdanyachi chutney (best! I’ll make a peanut butter version of this), choonda from a family friend and launji. My Aaji used to also make Suddharas which we used to sneak from her cupboard (the same cupboard I now have in Goa with me).
Look for the spiciest, hottest red chilli. Normally we do a mix of these thin, long ones and also the round, fat ones which are vaguely called ‘Gujarati chilli’ by Shaila. 
The important part is leaving it outside for a day or two to ‘murofy’ or basically change colour, ferment a bit and become the FIRE HOT RED thecha that we all love. 
Which pickles do you make at home? I love those north India brinjal, carrot and garlic pickles!! 
And our friend in Chandigarh makes the most amazing non-veg pickles following the Maharaja of Patiala’s recipes!
Send me your favorite pickle recipe and I’ll make it and tag you!

THECHA
1/2 kg spicy red chillies
1/4 cup lemon juice
1/2 cup neutral oil (we used groundnut)
2 tbsp salt

Method-
1. Take off the stems and wash chillies properly. Let them dry out in the sun or pat them dry (if there is any moisture, it spoils faster)
2. Put 1/2 chillies in the mixer and process a bit (be CAREFUL when you open the lid, it’s HOT). Add the rest of the chillies and other ing. Process properly.
3. Keep in a bowl with a lid outside for 2 days. Then transfer to ziploc bags and freeze or keep in the fridge for approx 2 months.

How to buy food!
And what questions to ask. Are vitally important. 
1. Where does your food come from- there ain’t no point buying organic if it’s travelling across the planet to get to you yo!
2. How is it grown/ collected/ made- this goes beyond ‘organic’ certification. You can only be sure if you start participating in your community, in your locality. I really loved going to the @sharanindia Juhu Farmer’s market when I lived in Bombay 
3. What is the method- It can be a traditional method, a forgotten artisan, a kacchi ghani ka tel, a desi egg, a homemade pickle.

I know I piss people off with my generic blanket statements like we should all eat organic food and AGAIN I say, this is a consideration for the upwardly mobile and only those who can afford.. let’s say.. smart phones. Or can afford to travel a couple of times a year. Or can buy this kids new clothes for festivals. If you can do all this, thinking about how your food is grown, who grows it, how it is processed and who gets paid for it, is important.

latestIgtvVideos.title: Sumi Ma’s bread and butter pudding
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Aaji was my last surviving grand-parent so you all know a lot about her but not much about my maternal grand-mum. Sumati Joglekar nee Gupte was an actress and incredible cook! And I inherited her cookbook!
But her repertoire didn’t stop at just kalvans and bhujanas. She went to ‘English’ cooking classes to a British lady who taught her how to make classics like Caramel Custard and Bread & Butter Pudding. 
So from my grandmother, mother and me to you- here is this beautiful piece of our heart made perfect in this most beautiful oven, the @morphyrichardsindia Luxechef OTG that crisps the top and keeps the pudding moist and delicious from the inside.

Now you know where the good hair genes and the amazing recipes come from! And you know what? She didn’t care about gluten, dairy, refined sugar or trans fats. She made this as a treat once in a while and lived to a ripe old age!

Sumi Ma’s Bread and Butter Pudding

4 cups bread without crusts(stale bread better or brioche/ raisin bread)
1/4 cup soaked golden raisins
1/2 cup chocolate chips (optional, it tastes as good without)
Mixture-
3 eggs
2 cups milk
1 1/4 cup cream
1/2 cup sugar 
3 tbsp + 2 tbsp butter (half before baking, half after)
1 tsp vanilla extract
1 tsp cinnamon powder

Method-
1. Cut crusts of the bread. Cut into 2” cubes
2. Mix milk, sugar, eggs, cream, vanilla, cinnamon powder and whisk well (till sugar dissolves) 
3. Soak bread cubes in it for 15-20 min
4. Butter oven proof dish and put 1/2 bread cubes. Add raisins and chocolate chips. Cover with the rest of the bread. 
5. Put 3 tbsp butter on the surface. Bake at 180 degrees centrigrade for 25/30 min till the crust is nice and brown. 
6. Brush with remaining butter once you remove it.

MORNING CORTISOL DRINK + ADRENAL BURNOUT FATIGUE ANXIETY! CHECK OUT MY SUMMER CORTISOL DRINK PINNED ON GRID
What have we women done to ourselves!
As we get older and our hormones think they are at a non-stop rave with uppers and downers
We MUST slow down and take time to really understand our bodies and what we want from life!
Right?? Right!
Your adrenal glands sit on top of your kidney and make those fightercock hormones Cortisol & Adrenaline! 
I’m currently going through v.serious peri menopause symptoms (I check everything on those ‘do you have symptoms like these’ lists including night sweats, anxiety, heart palpitations and my last blood work showed my cortisol was off the charts. And whenever I feel like this, COFFEE makes me feel like I’m going to have a panic attack (even though I put MCT oil & mushroom powder in it!)
So when I saw this Cortisol Morning Tonic on @itsnicolejaques page (I’ve modified it a bit) and when SO many of you asked me for the recipe, I realised we are ALL IN THE SAME ADRENAL CRASH BOAT!
Which comes from trying to do it all, have it all, control it all, smash it all, hit it out of the park, be a #girlboss, be a fantastic mom etc.
Also Vit C + Zinc is v. Good for adrenals as is Magnesium + Ashwa to sleep (pls always do your bloody work & check with a doc before you start any supplements).

I’m off for a 5 day ALL WOMEN tantra retreat to try and ground, connect, slow down and start taking pleasure in the juiciness of each moment.

MORNING CORTISOL DRINK

Ingredients 
MORNING CORTISOL PRE-MIX
¼ cup Haldi powder 
¼ cup Cinnamon Powder 
¼ cup Ginger powder 
¼ cup Fennel seeds
1 tbsp pink salt

MORNING CORTISOL DRINK 
1tsp Pre-Mix
2 cups Hot water 
1 whole lemon (juiced)
1 cap Apple Cider Vinegar
1 tbsp Honey (don’t put in boiling water/ very hot water!)

Method 
PRE MIX - mix all the dry powder ingredients in a jar together 
DRINK - heat water. Add lime juice , acv , honey ( dont add to boiling water). Add 1 tsp of the pre mixed cortisol powder or 1/4 tsp of each dry powder

FIRSTLY, before you go running to buy yams and order bio-identical hormones, THIS POST IS TO SHARE INFO & MY JOURNEY and the decision to get on any kind of HRT (hormone replacement therapy, remember this I won’t keep typing it again and again 😂) has to be done via a functional doctor or Gynac who is an expert in this field and there are several contraindications so this is serious stuff guys, it’s not like taking spirulina or popping magnesium ok!
Phew long disclaimer.
Now, if you are in your late thirties or over, chances are, all conversations with your friends start like this-
God I’m just sweating like crazy.
I can’t sleep.
I have severe anxiety.
My shoulder hurts.
Super brain fog.
I hate everyone around me.
Et cetera.

During one of these conversations on the beach, I met a lovely lady who was like, I’ve been on HRT for 10 years and I had zero peri-menopause symptoms and just sailed through. Confirmed by another lovely friend in Bali who is on bio identical HRT also.

Heh? What’s HRT? I’m super woke and aware. Why hadn’t I heard of it. Don’t women go through perimenopause in India? In fact, we go through a longer and earlier period-menopause than most!

Further digging made me discover that HRT is seen with great suspicion and was banned by the FDA because of a few studies that linked it to Breast Cancer. Yikes! What! That’s why I say always do your own research!

Next, I became a part of a wonderful group called Menopausers In Mumbai run by the lovely @rachelsreflexologyclinic and found many women thriving on BIO IDENTICAL HRT (different from regular HRT). 

Now here is the deal from the doc who prescribed it to me.
The DIFFERENCE between BIO IDENTICAL HRT & REGULAR HRT is that bio identical hormones cannot be patented!
So in regular HRT, there is a small change made by big pharma. Which your body doesn’t accept so easily and might cause other side effects.
Whereas BIO HRT, are hormones (progesterone etc) identical to what is found in your body and usually from a plant derived source.
Ping Rachel to get on the WhatsApp group, it’s a treasure of resources!
#perimenopause #bioidenticalhormonetherapy

Thank GODDESS my parents are here!!
It’s been amazing to have them be sounding boards, to just huddle down into family and unconditional love and support.
Life will continue to blow up in our faces and the real work is how present you can be, how grateful you can be for what you have unconditionally and the evolution that every challenge throws up.
So here is who I am.
I’m a chef (not a nutritionist, yet. I’m studying to be one).
I run a very successful fine dining gourmet catering Company @gaiagourmet.in 
On Instagram, I take simple recipes and add nutrient density to them. 
I’m deeply interested in holistic health.
I experiment on myself and my kid and share those experiments.
I always have started with the disclaimer that I believe everyone here has their own brain, will do their own research and will verify and use their own discernment before following what ANYONE has to say on social media.
I actually believe my audience is intelligent.
But boy can they be mean.
So that makes me want to be a little more protective of my energy.
And I’m so so so grateful for my parents, my family and my real life.
Empowering yourself doesn’t need to come at the cost of tearing others down.

So here is dahi chia cucumber pohe that my dad’s Akka aaji used to give them as a snack, reinvented as a nutrient dense, probiotic, high protein, gorgeous summer dish.
Hope you enjoy it.

DAHI CHIA POHE

2 cup dahi
2-3 tbsp chia seeds
1/2 tsp salt
1 tsp sugar
1/2 tsp jeera powder
3-4 small cucumbers

Tadka
1 tbsp oil
Ping hing
1/8th tsp rai
3-4 tbsp pohe
2 tbsp peanuts
1 tsp flax seeds
1/2 green chilli

METHOD
1. MIX- dahi, salt, sugar, jeera powder. Add cucumber strips
2. TADKA- heat oil and add tadka ingredients. Fry till pohe are crispy and fluffed up.
3. POUR- pohe on dahi cucumber mix just before eating

EASY AAM PAPAD ROLL UPS!

2 cups mango puree
1/2 cup sugar (adjust depending on how sweet your mango is and how sour you want your aam papad)
Juice of 1 lime
Optional flavours- ilaichi powder & saffron for sweet
Chilli powder, black salt, chaat masala & jeera powder for spiced
Ghee for the tray

METHOD
1. COOK- mango puree & sugar in a pan for 10 min till it’s reduced. Add lemon juice and flavouring. 
2. SPREAD- into ghee greased tray. Set the AIR CRISP to dehydrator mode and dehydrate for 6-8 hours.
3. CUT- remove from tray and cut into little squares and place on top of each other or long strips and roll to make Aam papad rolls up

2 MIN CHILLI OIL RICE PAPER NOODLES 

Have you ever been to @dintaifungsg ? Not only do they have the BEST DIMSUM in the world, their hand pulled noodles are stuff of LEGEND!
So how about a copycat version that took me literally one second, ok fine, 5 minutes to make.
Who knew that if you cut rice paper into strips and soaked them very briefly in hot water and make a super fast chilli oil (with added good fat cashew butter), it becomes the silkiest, most delicious, easiest noodle dish!

And if you haven’t been to dintaifung , it’s all over Asia & Dubai, please go eat there!

2 MIN CHILLI OIL RICE PAPER NOODLES 

4-8 rice paper 
Hot water

Chilli Oil
1 tbsp chopped garlic
1 tsp gochujang / chilli flakes
1 tbsp sesame 
1 tbsp cashew butter/ peanut butter/ tahini/ coconut milk
1 tbsp sugar (optional)
1 tbsp light soya sauce
4 tbsp hot vegetable oil

METHOD
1. SOAK- cut rice paper into strips and soaked in warm water for 2 min
2. CHILLI OIL- Put all chilli oil ingredients in a heatproof bowl, heat oil to smoking point, pour on top of ingredients and mix.
3. MIX- add soaked noodles into the chilli oil mix. Top with spring onions & sesame & YENJOY!

SOL KADHI/ KOKUM SAAR (eat with kurkurit fried fish & rice)

Good old Kokum (Garcinia Indica) ohooohoho that pink colour, those plump pods sold by grumpy Goan maushis from wooden bowls/ buckets (1 bucket for 100 bucks), those sour bits of flavour that sit slowly leaching colour into your fish curry or into your Urrak, a little kokam sherbet or Sol kadhi served with a fish Thali to help in digestion (after all that rice!)

Declared a super-food by UNFAO and Rujuta Divekar, my favorite Kokum is being touted as the new antacid and guardian of all that gut flora in your system!
And also I LOVE it. It’s cooling, sour, pink and pretty! 
It’s a digestion aid, it’s anti-bacterial, anti-viral and antioxidant phew!
It’s perfect for pregnancy nausea and summer hydration and way better to give to your kids than overly sweetened packaged fruit juice so it’s basically AWESOME!
Remember to make it only with fresh coconut milk! 
Eat with fried prawns and rice and enjoy!! Or as a drink for these sweltering, humid end of summer days! I think I got some Kokum on steroids coz DAMN THAT’S PINK!

Earrings are from @zara before you ask 😂

Kokum Saar/ Sol Kadhi 
15-20 Kokum soaked in 1 cup water (8- 10 tbsp Kokum Water once soaked)
1 cup coconut milk ( made from fresh grated coconut & water) do not use powdered or canned!
1 tsp Ginger paste
1 tsp mild Green Chilly paste
2 tsp Sugar
1 tsp Jeera Powder
Salt to taste (3/4 TSP- 1TSP)
1 tsp washed and finely chopped Coriander

Method 
SOAK- kokum in hot water and keep aside for 20 mins 
GRIND - fresh coconut with water and make coconut milk. Take it through a sieve to get fresh coconut milk 
MIX - to the coconut milk , add ginger paste or juice, green chilli paste , salt , soaked kokum juice , jeera powder and sugar. Mix together 
GARNISH - with fresh coriander leaves
